**Optimization Insight**  
- All nibble and float32 interleaving happens in NEON registers; there are NO stack spills/loads anywhere.  
- `vmlaq_lane_f32` enables "broadcast a single float lane as a vector" with minimal instruction count, ideal for GEMM on small groups.
- This pattern is scalable for K_TILE > 1 via kernel loop unrolling, and seamless for AArch64-A76/A78-class devices.
- Avoiding intermediate float arrays reduces DRAM pressure and power; all core math happens in NEON FPU pipeline.

**How to proceed:**
- Integrate this microkernel into your multi-threaded/streaming MMC runtime, arranging the inner K tiling to call this microkernel as the core GEMM.  
- CPU feature detection should check for NEON (AArch64 always has it) and optionally ARMv8.2+FP16 for native half-float conversion.
- Profile on real device; tune N_TILE, M_TILE, and kernel unrolls for your chip.

